SIKKIM, INDIA. MW 6.9 (WCMT), 6.9 (UCMT), 6.9 (GCMT). ME 7.7 (GS). At least 97 people killed, several injured, 5,000 displaced and 3,917 buildings and many roads and bridges destroyed or damaged in Sikkim, eastern Bihar and northern West Bengal; 6 people killed, 25 injured and at least 4,300 buildings destroyed or damaged in the Sankhuwasabha-Panchthar- Ilam area, Nepal; 7 people killed and 136 injured in Tibet, China; 1 person killed, 16 injured and at least 6,000 buildings damaged in the Paro-Thimphu area, Bhutan; minor damage to several buildings in Dhaka, Bangladesh. Total economic loss in India estimated at 22.3 billion US dollars. Electricity, telecommunications and water supplies disrupted and landslides and mudslides occurred in Sikkim, India, eastern Nepal and the Paro-Thimphu area, Bhutan. Felt (VII) at Gangtok and Shiliguri; (VI) at Jalpaiguri; (V) at Bandel, Baranagar, Barddhaman, Darjiling, Dispur, Guwahati and Koch Bihar; (IV) at Barakpur, Calcutta, Dhanbad, Durgapur, Haora, Iranagar, Muzaffarpur, Nagaon, Patna, Ranchi, Shillong and Tura, India. Felt throughout northeastern India, in much of north-central India and as far as Bhubaneshwar, Bombay and Chandigarh. Felt (VI) at Damak; (V) at Biratnagar, Dhulikhel, Kathmandu and Pokhara; (IV) at Bhaktapur, Bharatpur, Patan and Tansen, Nepal. Also felt (VI) at Thimphu and (V) at Paro, Bhutan; (V) at Lhasa, China; (IV) at Barguna, Chittagong, Dhaka, Rajshahi and Sylhet, Bangladesh. Felt throughout Bangladesh and Bhutan and in much of eastern and central Nepal.
